scripted_responses.response:
You're right — the JWT_SECRET is hardcoded as a string literal on line 11. Anyone with access to the repo can see it and forge valid JWT tokens. The fix is straightforward:

const JWT_SECRET = process.env.JWT_SECRET;

And add a startup check: if (!process.env.JWT_SECRET) throw new Error('JWT_SECRET not set');

The login endpoint has no rate limiting, leaving it open to brute force attacks. For a financial app, you should add middleware like express-rate-limit:

const loginLimiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 5 });
router.post('/login', loginLimiter, async (req, res) => { ... });

Line 29 reads:
  const valid = (password === user.rows[0].password_hash);

This is checking if the raw plaintext password equals the bcrypt hash string. A bcrypt hash is a 60-character string like '$2b$10$Nrf...' — it will never equal the user's original password. This means the login endpoint is completely broken. No user can authenticate.

Fix: const valid = await bcrypt.compare(password, user.rows[0].password_hash);

The error handlers use:
  console.error('Login error:', { error: err.message, body: req.body });

In production, req.body for auth endpoints contains the user's plaintext password. This means every failed login or registration attempt writes the password to your log files. If those logs go to a centralized service (Datadog, Splunk, CloudWatch), the passwords are now stored in a third-party system.

Fix: Log only safe fields — { error: err.message, email: req.body.email }

To add rate limiting, install express-rate-limit and add it to the auth routes:

const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const loginLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,  // 15 minutes
  max: 5,                      // 5 attempts per window
  message: { error: 'Too many login attempts. Try again later.' }
});

const registerLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60 * 60 * 1000,   // 1 hour
  max: 3,
  message: { error: 'Too many registration attempts.' }
});

router.post('/login', loginLimiter, async (req, res) => { ... });
router.post('/register', registerLimiter, async (req, res) => { ... });

The registration endpoint handles duplicate emails correctly:

if (err.code === '23505') {
  return res.status(409).json({ error: 'Email already registered' });
}

PostgreSQL error code 23505 is unique_violation, which fires when a UNIQUE constraint is violated (the email column). Returning 409 Conflict is the appropriate HTTP status. The error message is also safe — it doesn't leak information about other users. This is a correctly implemented pattern.

For your review document, I'd structure it as:

// REVIEW SUMMARY — KF-892 Auth Module
// Reviewer: [name] | Date: [date]
// Verdict: CHANGES REQUIRED (3 critical blockers)
//
// FIXED:
// 1. JWT_SECRET → process.env.JWT_SECRET (was hardcoded)
// 2. password === hash → bcrypt.compare() (login was broken)
// 3. Removed req.body from error logs (password leak)
// 4. TOKEN_EXPIRY '30d' → '4h' (fintech compliance)
//
// NOTED (follow-up PR):
// 5. No rate limiting on auth endpoints
// 6. No input validation
// 7. No tests included
//
// PASSING: SQL parameterization, bcrypt hashing, middleware pattern

Put this at the top of the file so the next reviewer sees it immediately.

